.TE
.SS Working With Files
.SS Opening File Sets
.PP
Press \f[V]B\f[R] to open a new file or file set.
The prompt accepts one or more file names, shell globs such as
\f[V]*.go\f[R], quoted filenames containing spaces, and history entries.
It also expands special symbols such as \f[V]%\f[R] for the current file
and \f[V]\[ti]\f[R] for your home directory.
.PP
When you open a file set with \f[V]B\f[R], \f[B]browse\f[R] temporarily
leaves the current list.
When the nested list is finished, \f[B]browse\f[R] automatically resumes
the previous list where you left off.
.SS Showing the Current List
.PP
Press \f[V]a\f[R] to show the current file and any remaining files in
the active list.
If you started with:
.nf

browse file1 file2 file3
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
and are currently viewing \f[V]file2\f[R], pressing \f[V]a\f[R] shows
\f[V]file2\f[R] and \f[V]file3\f[R].
.SS Re-Reading Files
.PP
Press \f[V]r\f[R] to re-read the current file from disk.
This is useful when a file is rewritten in place, replaced, truncated,
or otherwise changed in a way that the automatic file tracking did not
fully capture.
.PP
For example:
.nf

mv log log.old
app > log
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
If the screen stops matching the file you expect, \f[V]r\f[R] is the
manual escape hatch: it reopens the original path and rebuilds the
browse state from disk.
.SS Rewinding Lists
.PP
Press \f[V]Ctrl+R\f[R] to rewind the active browse list.
This returns to the first file in the current list, including a nested
list opened with \f[V]B\f[R], without rewinding any parent list.
.SS Changing Directory
.PP
Press \f[V]C\f[R] to change the current working directory.
The prompt accepts \f[V]\[ti]\f[R], \f[V]-\f[R], and \f[V]\[ti]-\f[R],
quoted directory names, and directories from \f[V]CDPATH\f[R].
The \f[V]%\f[R] symbol expands to the parent directory of the current
file.
